<paragraph blockId="1.[148,977,604,944]" pageId="1" pageNumber="146">
The 
<typeStatus box="[215,302,737,758]" pageId="1" pageNumber="146">lectotype</typeStatus>
(SBL 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[365,383,737,757]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="146">¼</emphasis>
<quantity box="[388,465,737,758]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.6" pageId="1" pageNumber="146" unit="mm" value="5.6">5.6 mm</quantity>
; ABL 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[527,545,737,757]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="146">¼</emphasis>
about 6.0 mm) belongs to the 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Dejean" baseAuthorityYear="1828" box="[841,893,737,758]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Loxandrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="146" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="agilis">
<emphasis box="[841,893,737,758]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="146">agilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group. I cannot associate it with any species described by Allen (1972) but by its size and shape of pronotum, particularly the non protruding front angles, it looks more similar to members of 
<taxonomicName authority="Allen" authorityName="Allen" authorityYear="1972" box="[266,419,816,837]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Loxandrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="146" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="algidus">
<emphasis box="[266,361,816,837]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="146">L. algidus</emphasis>
Allen
</taxonomicName>
than to any other species seen. It differs from the 
<typeStatus box="[893,976,816,837]" pageId="1" pageNumber="146">holotype</typeStatus>
and 
<specimenCount box="[194,322,843,864]" pageId="1" pageNumber="146" type="generic" typeStatus="paratype">one paratype</specimenCount>
of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Allen" authorityYear="1972" box="[367,469,843,864]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Loxandrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="146" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="algidus">
<emphasis box="[367,469,843,864]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="146">L. algidus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
studied in having the antennae and legs entirely yellowish (
<emphasis bold="true" box="[255,275,870,890]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="146">6</emphasis>
reddish-black in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Allen" authorityYear="1972" box="[444,540,869,890]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Loxandrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="146" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="algidus">
<emphasis box="[444,540,869,890]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="146">L. algidus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), the elytral striae slightly shallower and less coarsely punctate, and the microsculpture on the proepisternum and metepisternum coarser.
</paragraph>
